            array (
                'id' => 1,
                'name' => 'Belfry and Cloth Hall',
                'address' => 'Markt 7',
                'lat' => '51.20',
                'lng' => '3.221',
                'description_a' => '<p>The Belfry of Bruges, or <i>Belfort</i>, is a medieval bell tower in the historical centre of Bruges. One of the city\'s most prominent symbols, the Belfry formerly housed a treasury and the municipal archives, and served as an observation post for spotting fires and other danger.</p>',
                'description_b' => '<p>The Belfry of Bruges was built around 1240, when Bruges was an important centre of the renowned Flemish cloth industry. The original tower was rebuilt after it was destroyed by fire in 1280, and the second segment was added not long after. The octagonal lantern dates from the end of the 15th century and was initially crowned by a wooden spire. After having been burnt down twice, it was never rebuilt.&nbsp;</p><p>The tower is 83 metres high and is part of the Cloth Hall, the main marketplace for textiles and other goods during the Middle Ages. Visitors can take the 366 steps to the top for a panoramic view of the city. The Belfry houses, amongst other things, the treasury room and the carillon with 47 bells that can be heard all over the city.</p><p>The Belfry tower was the symbol of the autonomy and pride of the city and its inhabitants. Like in most cities of the Low Countries, it was used as a watchtower and a treasury where legal documents and trade privileges were preserved. Until 1769, new laws and important messages were read out to the people from the balcony above the entrance door.&nbsp;</p><p>The Belfry also served as a handy communication tool between the city and its inhabitants via the ringing of its bells. Each bell carried a distinct sound and function, notifying citizens of the time, the opening and closing of the city gates, important events or dangers such as wars or fire. As such, the Belfry hasn’t only been the pride and protector of our city, but has also provided the soundtrack for life in Bruges since the Middle Ages.</p>',
