            1 => 
            array (
                'id' => 2,
                'name' => 'Statue of Jan Breydel and Pieter de Coninck',
                'address' => 'Markt',
                'lat' => '51.208',
                'lng' => '3.224',
                'description_a' => '<p>Our statue dates from 1887 and the pedestal below our feet represents scenes of important events in our city’s history, like the Matins of Bruges and the Battle of the Golden Spurs.</p>',
                'description_b' => '<p>My name is Pieter de Coninck, an eloquent weaver from Bruges, and to my right is my friend Jan Breydel, a local butcher. Together we led the revolt of Flemish insurgents against the attempts by our French lieges to annex Flanders and tax our growing wealth. The uprising resulted in the massacre of a French garrison stationed in Bruges in the early hours of the 18th of May, 1302, an event that would become known as the Matins of Bruges.&nbsp;</p><p>According to the tradition, to distinguish the French from the natives, anyone suspected to be French was obliged to repeat the phrase ‘<i>scilt ende vrient</i>’, meaning ‘shield and friend’ - a phrase that is hard to pronounce for French speakers. Those who were unable to properly pronounce the words got their heads bashed in with a <i>Goedendag</i>, or Good Day: a rudimentary weapon that consisted of a stick with a large metal pin. For the 120 Frenchies who came in close contact with it that morning, it didn’t turn out to be a very good day!</p><p>The French governor Jacques de Chatillon managed to escape the city dressed as a commoner and inform King Philip the Fair in Paris of the massacre that had taken place here. Infuriated, &nbsp;the king gathered an army of his finest knights and sent them off to Bruges to teach us a lesson. An alliance of Flemish forces, consisting mostly of foot soldiers, ambushed the French cavalry on a swampy field near the city of Courtrai and slaughtered the royal army at the Battle of the Golden Spurs on July 11, 1302. Even though we eventually lost the war, the battle has become a symbol for the Flemish strive for independence and the 11th of July is still celebrated every year as the Day of the Flemish Community.</p>',
                'description_c' => NULL,
