                'deleted_at' => NULL,
                'url' => 'http://peanutagency.synology.me:5018/storage/26/60a9a71cbc595_800px-Statue_of_Jan_Breydel_and_Pieter_de_Coninck_03.jpg',
            ),
            2 => 
            array (
                'id' => 3,
                'name' => 'Market Square',
                'address' => 'Markt',
                'lat' => '51.208',
                'lng' => '3.224',
                'description_a' => '<p>The Market square has always been the social and commercial heart of the city. It is dominated by the neo-Gothic Provincial Palace to the east and the Belfry and Cloth Hall to the south.</p>',
            'description_b' => '<p>Bruges reached its commercial boom in the Late Middle Ages thanks to its established reputation as an export centre for Flemish cloth, its easy access to the North Sea and, from the 14th century onwards, the influence of the Burgundian court. At the crossroads between the <strong>Hanseatic cities (link to Wednesday Market)</strong> of Germany and Scandinavia as well as the most important commercial regions in France, England, Spain and Italy, Bruges acted as a hub for trade between northern and southern Europe.&nbsp;</p><p>Since 985, traders have held weekly markets on this square and continue to do so every Wednesday. Major events such as jousts, tournaments, fairs and processions took place here, as well as executions that always drew large crowds. The square was also the scene of many social protests throughout the turbulent history of Bruges, as well as important ceremonies such as prominent marriages or institutions of new sovereigns.&nbsp;</p>',
                'description_c' => NULL,
                'created_at' => '2021-05-21 09:07:53',
                'updated_at' => '2021-08-17 02:55:33',
                'deleted_at' => NULL,
                'url' => 'http://peanutagency.synology.me:5018/storage/29/611b251dedb88_bruges1.jpeg',
            ),
            3 => 
            array (
                'id' => 4,
                'name' => 'Provincial Palace',
                'address' => 'Markt 3',
                'lat' => '51.2088',
                'lng' => '3.2250',
                'description_a' => '<p>On the east side of the Market square you find the Provincial Palace, an impressive neo-Gothic building that dates back to the 19th century.&nbsp;</p>',
            'description_b' => '<p>The Provincial Palace is located on the spot where the medieval Water Hall once stood, a covered arcade where commercial ships could sail through to load and unload goods sheltered from the wind and rain. The imposing Water Hall, 95 meters long, 24 metres wide and 30 metres high, contained many shops and houses and the upper floor served as one big storage space.&nbsp;</p><p>The Water Hall was well known to traders from all over Europe. Ships made their way from the North Sea to the nearby ports of Sluis or Damme, where goods were transferred onto small barges. From there, these barges could make it into Bruges via a small canal, passing underneath the low urban bridges until they reached the Water Hall in the commercial heart of the city. The Water Hall stood here from 1294 to 1787 and was replaced by the Provincial Palace a century later. In case you’re wondering what happened to the river, it continues to flow underneath the building today.&nbsp;</p><p>On the left side of the Provincial Palace is the <strong>Historium museum (link to Historium)</strong>, an immersive virtual experience that brings medieval Bruges back to life, including the old Water Hall. Make sure to take a look inside if you have the chance!</p>',
                'description_c' => NULL,
                'created_at' => '2021-05-21 09:37:25',
                'updated_at' => '2021-08-17 01:29:24',
                'deleted_at' => NULL,
