            6 => 
            array (
                'id' => 7,
                'name' => 'Guild houses on the Market square',
                'address' => 'North side of Markt',
                'lat' => '51.20929780770058',
                'lng' => '3.2239757889686',
                'description_a' => '<p>The north side of the Markt behind me is characterised by the houses with stepped gables, a style typical for Flanders. Many of these houses served as guild houses.</p>',
            'description_b' => '<p>A guild was an association of workers who practiced the same profession. Each guild drew up rules for its members and exchanged knowledge and experience. Before being allowed to practice the craft, one first had to learn the job as an apprentice and pass a master test. In this way, each guild kept a strict control over who was allowed to join their ranks. The guilds looked after the interests of their workers, arranged commercial disputes between members and fixed the salaries and the prices of their products. The guilds also offered a form of social security to their members by way of sick and poor care, and can thus be regarded as precursors to trade unions.&nbsp;</p><p>The guilds occupied many seats in the Flemish city councils, which made them extremely powerful. In my days, the count needed to have permission from the city councils of the three largest cities in Flanders - Bruges, Gent and Ypres - to make all kinds of decisions, even whom he was to marry. In this way, the guilds exerted a considerable influence on the governance of the entire county.&nbsp;</p><p>The guilds also played a prominent military role, as they provided the militias that formed the army of Flanders. They defended their economic and political privileges fiercely against anyone who opposed them, be it the count of Flanders or the king of France. This often resulted in large-scale protests or even armed conflict, like the <strong>Battle of the Golden Spurs (link to Statue of Jan Breydel and Pieter de Coninck)</strong> that was won by the militias of the Flemish guilds. All this made the guilds the effective rulers of Flanders and the defenders of the political and economic status quo all throughout the Middle Ages.&nbsp;</p><p>Many of the guild houses were lavishly decorated to express the wealth and power of the guild. This row of houses includes Le Panier d\'Or, the guild house of the tilers, and La Civière d\'Or, the craft house of the fishermen and fishmongers.</p>',
                'description_c' => NULL,
                'created_at' => '2021-05-21 10:03:38',
                'updated_at' => '2021-05-21 11:03:55',
