            7 => 
            array (
                'id' => 8,
                'name' => 'Pro Patria Arch',
                'address' => 'Kartuizerinnenstraat 2',
                'lat' => '51.20738893947064',
                'lng' => '3.225157398166285',
                'description_a' => '<p>The Pro Patria Arch was built in 1929 to remember all the citizens of Bruges who lost their lives during the First World War.</p>',
                'description_b' => '<p>Behind the arch you can find a monument with the names of the victims of both World Wars, during which Bruges was occupied by the Germans. As the monument shows, far more citizens were killed in WWI than in WWII.&nbsp;</p><p>During the First World War, many young men from Bruges fought alongside the British, French and later American forces against the Germans and many lost their lives on the battlefields of Flanders and northern France. The Germans also made civilian casualties in Bruges, as did the British during bombardments of the city. The British air force bombed Bruges with approximately 6000 bombs during the war, which were dropped by hand and lacked accuracy. As a result, 125 civilians were killed and many houses were destroyed, though none of the major historical buildings were badly damaged.</p><p>During World War II, no significant battles were fought in Bruges and there were far less casualties compared to World War I, but it could have been very different. At the end of the war, in September 1944, while Canadian forces were approaching Bruges, the German Commanding Officer Immo Hopmann received the order from Berlin to open up fire on the Canadian soldiers. Immo Hopmann realised that if he were to do that, the historical centre of Bruges would be destroyed and many civilians would be killed. For that reason, he refused to carry out the order and thanks to his brave decision, the city was spared.</p>',
                'description_c' => NULL,
                'created_at' => '2021-05-21 10:12:19',
                'updated_at' => '2021-05-21 11:01:09',
                'deleted_at' => NULL,
                'url' => NULL,
            ),
            8 => 
            array (
                'id' => 9,
                'name' => 'Gruuthuse Palace',
                'address' => 'Dijver 17',
                'lat' => '51.20515689732369',
                'lng' => '3.22502646933032',
                'description_a' => '<p>Welcome to my home, the palace of the Gruuthuse family. Have you noticed our family’s coat of arms above the entrance gate? The cannons refer to my role as military advisor to the dukes of Burgundy, and the necklace with the ram symbolises my membership of the Order of the Golden Fleece.&nbsp;</p>',
            'description_b' => '<p>The name Gruuthuse literally means house of <i>gruut</i>, which was a mix of spices that gave flavour and aroma to beer before hops were used. In my days, many households brewed their own beer, as it was much safer to drink than water. It was my family who was granted the monopoly on the import or sale of gruut, which made us incredibly wealthy and powerful. In fact, my family was so powerful that we were able to build our own private VIP chapel - for our Very Important Prayers - inside the <strong>Church of Our Lady (link to Church of Our Lady)</strong> with direct access to our bedroom.&nbsp;</p><p>It’s fair to say that I was the most famous member of my family. I was a businessman, military advisor, diplomat and patron of arts. I owned a library of manuscripts that was one of the largest of the time, and the so-called Gruuthuse Manuscript which carries my name is recognised as a masterpiece of Flemish art. My slogan can be seen above the entrance: ‘Plus Est En Vous’, meaning ‘There is more in you’.&nbsp;</p><p>I kept close ties to the dukes of Burgundy and in 1461, I was knighted into the Order of the Golden Fleece. This order was established in Bruges in 1430 by Duke Philip the Good with the aim to defend the Catholic religion, uphold the values of knighthood and increase the prestige of the Burgundian dynasty. It became one of the most respected orders in Europe. Knights of the order discussed politics and war with the duke and could never be summoned before an ordinary court of law, which meant we were above the law.&nbsp;</p><p>The order has had many prominent members over the course of history, like the Holy Roman Emperor Charles V or the English King Henry VIII. The order is still in existence today and counts Queen Elizabeth II, Nicolas Sarkozy and King Felipe VI among its members. The symbol of the order is a golden ram suspended from a necklace. According to a Greek myth, the Trojan hero Jason captured the fleece from a fierce dragon. The ram supports the claim of the Burgundians to be descended from the Trojans. You’ll find it not only in the coat of arms of my family, but in many places around the city if you keep an eye out for it.</p><p>I ordered the construction of this beautiful palace in the 15th century. It now houses the recently renovated Gruuthuse museum, which displays a broad collection of historical artefacts that offer an overview of the history of Bruges.</p>',
                'description_c' => NULL,
                'created_at' => '2021-05-21 10:50:56',
                'updated_at' => '2021-05-22 15:06:10',
