            9 => 
            array (
                'id' => 10,
                'name' => 'Saint John’s Hospital',
                'address' => 'Mariastraat 38',
                'lat' => '51.20417366578837',
                'lng' => '3.224227217212133',
                'description_a' => '<p>Welcome to the Saint Johnʼs hospital, which was established around 1150 and remained in function for more than eight hundred years.&nbsp;</p>',
                'description_b' => '<p>The hospital was named after the Order of Saint John, also known as the Knights Hospitallers, who provided refuge and care to pilgrims on their way to the Holy Land. For that purpose, the Hospitallers built a large network of hospitals across Europe. The order was also charged with the defence of Jerusalem and along with the Templars, it was the most respected military order in the Holy Land. The lamb with the flag is one of the symbols of the order and can be seen above the portal.&nbsp;</p><p>The hospital of Bruges is amongst the oldest and largest remaining ones in Europe and counts as a perfect prototype of a hospital in the Late Middle Ages. It initially consisted of a monastery and a couple of infirmaries, but kept on expanding for centuries to include a brewery, a graveyard, a pharmacy and several gardens and chapels. The hospital refers to <i>hospitalitas </i>or hospitality and was based on Christian charity, offering free care and shelter to pilgrims, the poor, the sick and the dying. The hospital was governed by the city, but the work was done by nuns and monks, like myself, on a voluntary basis.</p><p>In medieval times, spiritual care was considered much more important than physical care. Our primary task was to alleviate the souls of our patients and the hospital contained many chapels or altars devoted to saints who assisted in the healing process or the afterlife. For this reason, the hospital commissioned Hans Memling in 1489 to paint a shrine devoted to Saint Ursula, who protected school children from diseases. This masterpiece of Flemish art can still be found in the hospital museum today, along with several other paintings by Memling as well as many tools and instruments that were used here. Make sure to take a look inside if you have the chance!</p><p>Our community of monks and nuns also provided physical care, but we left more delicate tasks, like surgeries, amputations or the treatment of broken bones, to more specialised physicians. A popular way to treat illnesses in my days was via bloodletting, a procedure by which blood was withdrawn from a patient. For this practice, doctors required the help of barbers, not because they were the most skilled medics, but simply because they had the sharpest tools in town!</p><p>The hospital remained the principal care institution in Bruges until 1977, when a modern hospital was built outside the city walls and the medieval infirmaries were turned into a museum.</p>',
