            10 => 
            array (
                'id' => 11,
                'name' => 'Statue of Saint Rochus',
                'address' => 'Wijngaardstraat 19 + Oude Gentweg 169 + Oude Gentweg 27 + Rozendal 15',
                'lat' => '51.20197633387756 + 51.203047382040275 + 51.20279402423158 + 51.21164084268355',
                'lng' => '3.225016276668759 + 3.2335317990206622 + 3.2268640981661187 + 3.217364440494693',
                'description_a' => '<p>The plague, aka the Black Death, originated in China and travelled via the fleas living on the rats on board the merchant ships.</p>',
                'description_b' => '<p>After it arrived in Italy, the bacteria spread to the rest of the continent via the trading routes. Especially in the overcrowded and polluted cities of Europe, such as Bruges, the disease spread like wildfire. The impact was devastating: from 1347 to 1350 between one third and one half of the European population, or about twenty million people, perished. Those who contracted the pest died a painful death within three days, and only few survived the infection. I was one of the lucky survivors.</p><p>My name is Rochus and I was born in Montpellier around the year 1300. I gave away all my possessions to the poor and travelled through Europe to take care of people suffering from the plague. Eventually I got infected myself and isolated myself deep inside the woods in order not to infect anyone else. Suffering from the disease alone in the woods, I couldn’t get the food I needed. Luckily for me, a dog came to visit every day. The dog picked up old pieces of bread from the streets in a nearby town and brought them to me. Thanks to my saviour on four legs, I was able to survive and even heal from the disease. That’s when I received the order from God to go back to my hometown.</p><p>Upon my arrival, the people of my hometown didn’t recognise me and my own uncle accused me of being a spy. I was arrested and locked up in prison, where I continued to take care of the sick. I died in my cell eight years later. In 1485, my relics were brought from Montpellier to Venice and since then I’ve been honoured as the patron saint of the sick, the imprisoned and the dogs. I was one of the four hundred saints that provided protection from the pest and you can still find our statues all over town. You can easily recognise mine: I’m a pilgrim with a hat and a staff and I’m pulling up my skirt to show the healed scars of the infection on my leg. On my side you can see my loyal dog with a piece of bread in its mouth. For centuries, people prayed to me to receive protection from this terrible disease.</p>',
                'description_c' => NULL,
                'created_at' => '2021-05-21 11:40:40',
                'updated_at' => '2021-05-22 14:43:29',
                'deleted_at' => NULL,
                'url' => NULL,
            ),
            11 => 
            array (
                'id' => 12,
                'name' => 'Princely Beguinage of Bruges',
                'address' => 'Begijnhof',
                'lat' => '51.20134743768201',
                'lng' => '3.223126856012609',
                'description_a' => '<p>The Princely Beguinage of the Vineyard was founded in 1245 as a community where pious women could live together to perform <i>ora et labora</i> - work and prayer.&nbsp;</p>',
            'description_b' => '<p>In my days, our community included a church, an infirmary, a guesthouse, a bakery, some farm buildings and even a brewery. Under my supervision the ladies had to live according to a strict set of rules, perform charity work and contribute to a collective fund. Much of the charity work was done in the Saint John’s Hospital, taking care of the sick and dying, but we were also involved in other activities like weaving, brewing or copying religious texts.&nbsp;</p><p>As opposed to other monastic orders, beguines took temporary vows of obedience and chastity. Because we did not have to take full religious vows, we were allowed to keep personal belongings and switch back from a religious to a secular life. This meant that ladies could always turn to the beguinage in times of need and return to society when they were back on their feet. As such, the beguinage made a major contribution to the empowerment of women during the Middle Ages, which was not always well received by the patriarchy in Rome. During the 14th century, the Pope even condemned the order for heresy for some time.&nbsp;</p><p>Today, the site is no longer inhabited by beguines, but by sisters of the Order of Saint Benedict, who perform the daily services in the <strong>church (link to church)</strong>. Now governed by the city’s social services, the beguinage continues to support vulnerable women by providing housing to several unmarried ladies with low incomes. The beguinage of Bruges has been a UNESCO World Heritage Site since 1998 and counts as one of the best preserved. The site is at its most beautiful during the springtime, when the daffodils are in bloom.</p>',
                'description_c' => NULL,
                'created_at' => '2021-05-22 09:42:20',
                'updated_at' => '2021-05-22 09:42:20',
                'deleted_at' => NULL,
