            14 => 
            array (
                'id' => 15,
                'name' => 'Legend of the Swans',
                'address' => 'Wijngaardplein',
                'lat' => '51.20085352296183',
                'lng' => '3.2242954552545378',
                'description_a' => '<p>The swans are the symbol of Bruges and are here because of me, Maximilian of Austria.</p>',
            'description_b' => '<p>To tell you that story, we need to go back to 1482, when my beloved wife, the Duchess Mary of Burgundy, fell off her horse during a hunting party and perforated her lung. She was taken to the hospital and died of internal bleedings at the <strong>Prince’s Court (link to Prince’s Court)</strong> two weeks later.</p><p>Our son Philip the Handsome was only four years old at the time and too young to take over power, so I was appointed regent of the Burgundian state until Philip was old enough to rule. Being the son of the German emperor and heir to both the Burgundian and Habsburgian territories, I was one of the most powerful men in Europe at the time. To secure my inheritance for myself and my son, I got involved in a series of conflicts with King Louis XI of France. To finance these wars, I had no other option but to increase taxes in my Burgundian territories, including the County of Flanders.</p><p>The rebellious and stubborn people of Bruges didn’t accept me as their ruler, and refused to pay higher taxes. In January 1488, they did the unthinkable. Upon entering the city, the people of Bruges closed the city gates behind me and took me hostage in the <strong>house of Craenenburg (link to Craenenburg)</strong> on the Market square. They tried to make a deal with me for months, but I refused to give in. Until my friend Pieter Lanchals, or Peter Longneck, who was the city administrator and one of my close advisors, was captured and brought onto the square. The bastards of Bruges tortured and executed Peter while I had to witness the whole scene from my prison cell. Eventually, I agreed to their terms and promised to renounce my regency over Flanders. They forced me to swear an oath not to punish the city and after four long months, I was finally released.</p><p>As soon as I was freed, I sought revenge. I gathered my troops outside the walls and besieged the city. When peace was finally made after years of conflict, I forced the people of Bruges to tear down their defense walls and banned all foreign merchants from the city. Bruges never fully recovered from this devastating blow. Meanwhile, the Zwin, the body of water connecting Bruges to the North Sea, had begun to silt and ships could no longer reach the city. To make matters worse, a crisis in the cloth industry resulted in less commercial activity while Bruges suffered from the competition of the bigger port of Antwerp. As Antwerp rose to become the main trading centre in the Low Countries, Bruges fell into decline. It wasn’t until the creation of the new harbour of Zeebrugge and the advent of tourism centuries later, that the economic revival could begin.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>Still, that wasn’t enough for me and I had one final punishment in store for the rebellious people of Bruges. To commemorate the murder of my friend Peter Longneck, I obliged them to keep \'longnecks\' in the city for forever and three days. The locals have kept this promise by taking care of the swans, even though I didn’t keep my promise to them...</p>',
                'description_c' => NULL,
                'created_at' => '2021-05-22 10:04:52',
                'updated_at' => '2021-05-22 10:04:52',
                'deleted_at' => NULL,
                'url' => NULL,
            ),
            15 => 
            array (
                'id' => 16,
                'name' => 'Lake of Love',
                'address' => 'Minnewater',
                'lat' => '51.20049659875906',
                'lng' => '3.224776472236397',
                'description_a' => '<p>The Minnewater, also known as the Lake of Love, is one of the most romantic places in Bruges. It was formed in the 12th century after a lock was put in place here along the river Reie.&nbsp;</p>',
            'description_b' => '<p>The name of the lake refers to an old legend that goes back to Roman times, when I fell in love with a beautiful lady named Minna. Sadly, because we belonged to two rival tribes, Minna’s father forbade her to marry me and instead arranged for her to marry another man.&nbsp;</p><p>In despair, Minna decided to run away from home and ended up lost in the woods. When the news reached me that Minna was missing, I went to look for her. A few days later I found Minna on the banks of the river, but it was too late. Starved and exhausted, she died in my arms. I was heartbroken. To honour Minna, I decided to build a dam to hold back the river, bury Minna underneath and flood her grave with water. On a rock next to the river I carved the words ‘Minna Water’. For that reason, the citizens of Bruges still call this lake Minnewater and the rock on which I carved her name is said to be buried underneath the <strong>Poertoren (link to Poertoren)</strong> on the side of the lake.&nbsp;</p><p>Many couples come to the bridge next to the tower to throw some coins in the water for good fortune.</p>',
                'description_c' => NULL,
                'created_at' => '2021-05-22 10:15:19',
                'updated_at' => '2021-05-22 10:15:19',
                'deleted_at' => NULL,
                'url' => NULL,
            ),
            16 => 
            array (
                'id' => 17,
                'name' => 'Poertoren',
                'address' => 'Begijnenvest 1',
                'lat' => '51.198621511544474',
                'lng' => '3.2235536764484416',
                'description_a' => '<p>The Poertoren protected the lake during the time it was used as an inner harbour.</p>',
            'description_b' => '<p>Its name, which literally means powder tower, refers to its former use as a storage space for gunpowder. The tower was part of the <strong>ramparts (link to City gates)</strong>, which were built in the 14th century and surrounded large parts of the city. The ramparts included a series of city gates as well as defence towers, this one being the best preserved. Most of the city’s defences are now gone, but you can still admire four medieval city gates along the ramparts, along with four remaining <strong>windmills (link to wind mills)</strong>.</p><p>The castle de la Faille bordering the lake was built in 1893 by a wealthy trader and now functions as a restaurant.</p>',
                'description_c' => NULL,
                'created_at' => '2021-05-22 10:22:16',
                'updated_at' => '2021-05-22 10:22:16',
                'deleted_at' => NULL,
                'url' => NULL,
            ),
            17 => 
            array (
                'id' => 18,
                'name' => 'Legend of the Bruges Fools',
                'address' => 'Walplein',
                'lat' => '51.202519559982406',
                'lng' => '3.2243476215017526',
                'description_a' => '<p>Did you know that the people of Bruges are nicknamed the \'<i>Brugse Zotten</i>\' or \'Fools of Bruges\'? It is me who gave them this name five hundred years ago, when the city of Bruges needed to build a new mental hospital.&nbsp;</p>',
            'description_b' => '<p>To do so, they needed permission from me, Maximilian of Austria. As you may already know, I didn’t get along very well with the people of Bruges after they imprisoned me and executed my loyal supporter <strong>Peter Longneck (link to Legend of the Swans)</strong> in front of my eyes. Thus, the city of Bruges tried to regain my favour by inviting me to town and holding a big celebration in my honour. Never one to turn down a good party, I accepted.&nbsp;</p><p>When I arrived, everybody was dressed up, people were dancing on the streets and many of them had already drunk far too much. It certainly was an interesting spectacle to behold! It was at that moment that the city’s administrators approached me and asked my permission to build a new mental hospital. I couldn’t contain my laughter and replied, “Just shut the gates of the city and you’ll have your mental hospital, because you’re all crazy!” Hilarious, isn’t it?! Ever since my clever remark, the people of Bruges have been nicknamed the ‘Fools of Bruges’.&nbsp;</p><p>The brewery on this square dates back to 1865. It is called the Half Moon and is where the famous Brugse Zot or Bruges Fool beer is brewed. From here, an underground pipeline transports the beer to the bottling plant three kilometres further with the aim to keep beer-filled trucks out of our narrow streets. You can spot a replica of the pipeline through a transparent manhole cover at the entrance of the brewery.&nbsp;</p>',
                'description_c' => NULL,
                'created_at' => '2021-05-22 12:38:24',
                'updated_at' => '2021-05-22 12:38:24',
                'deleted_at' => NULL,
                'url' => NULL,
            ),
            18 => 
            array (
                'id' => 19,
                'name' => 'Stoofstraat',
                'address' => 'Stoofstraat 3-5',
                'lat' => '51.2032766339493',
                'lng' => '3.224437752786963',
                'description_a' => '<p>The Stoofstraat or Stove Street is one of the narrowest streets in Bruges. The stove refers to the public bathhouses that were lined along this street during the 14th and 15th centuries.</p>',
                'description_b' => '<p>In my days, houses didn’t have baths and hygiene was not optimal, so people came to little alleys like this to wash themselves in a wooden tub heated by a fire. The bathhouses were spread throughout the city and were generally visited by nobles or wealthy merchants like myself. Often meals were served, accompanied by musicians playing music, and ladies offered pleasures of the flesh. As a result of these practices, Bruges became a hotspot for prostitution in Europe.&nbsp;</p><p>You can still spot a symbol of prostitution at the entrance of the alley, above the blue door. At a time when most people were illiterate, the curls represented two swans facing away from each other. When swans look towards each other, their necks form a heart shape symbolising love. But when they face away from each other, it meant that there was no real love here, only temporary love. Because the bathhouses began to earn a bad reputation, they were banned by the city in the 16th century. The Stoofstraat now features small boutiques and a cozy restaurant.</p>',
                'description_c' => NULL,
                'created_at' => '2021-05-22 12:47:48',
                'updated_at' => '2021-05-22 12:48:13',
                'deleted_at' => NULL,
                'url' => NULL,
            ),
            19 => 
            array (
                'id' => 20,
                'name' => 'God House \'Rooms Convent\'',
                'address' => 'Katelijnestraat 9-19',
                'lat' => '51.20356005449837',
                'lng' => '3.2249054716765486',
                'description_a' => '<p>Former almshouse ‘<i>Rooms Convent</i>’ or ‘Roman Convent’ is the oldest surviving almshouse in Bruges, dating back to 1330.&nbsp;</p>',
                'description_b' => '<p>A great number of these whitewashed almshouses can be found scattered around the city. They were established from the 14th century onwards by guilds and wealthy townspeople to serve as public housing for the poor. Even though Bruges was a prosperous city, there was still a lot of poverty among the population. The guilds built these almshouses, or god houses as we call them here, to provide housing for retired workers. The rich did the same for the poor, hoping that their work of mercy would guarantee them a spot in heaven.</p><p>The god houses all have a number of things in common: they are small, white houses built around a courtyard, most of them have a small garden, and all of them have a little chapel at the entrance where residents were obliged to pray three times per day for the salvation of the founders. Over forty of these communities are left within the old walls of Bruges and they still serve as homes for the elderly or for people with a low income. Almost all of the almshouses have been carefully restored and modernised to offer cosy living to today’s residents. Their picturesque gardens and whitewashed facades offer a welcoming retreat from the hustle and bustle of the city centre.</p>',
                'description_c' => NULL,
                'created_at' => '2021-05-22 12:56:05',
                'updated_at' => '2021-05-22 12:56:05',
                'deleted_at' => NULL,
                'url' => NULL,
            ),
            20 => 
            array (
                'id' => 21,
                'name' => 'Statue of Juan Luis Vives',
                'address' => 'O.-L.-Vrouwekerkhof-Zuid 6',
                'lat' => '51.20476125611365',
                'lng' => '3.225272489973212',
                'description_a' => '<p>My name is Juan Luis Vives and together with my friends Desiderius Erasmus and Thomas More, I was one of the most influential humanist scholars in the Low Countries.&nbsp;</p>',
            'description_b' => '<p>I’m originally from Valencia, but after my studies in Paris I settled in Bruges and became a professor at the University of Leuven. An expert on the subject of education, poverty and emancipation, my ideas laid the foundation of modern views on social reform, psychology and pedagogy. When the city of Bruges commissioned me to fix the growing problem of poverty amongst its citizens, I proposed a radically different approach towards poor relief based on schooling and governmental care. Unfortunately, I was confronted with serious opposition from religious authorities, who were keen to keep their lucrative hold over traditional aid based on charity.&nbsp;</p><p>I often resided in Oxford, where I taught Greek at the university and at the court of King Henry VIII and Catherine of Aragon. In 1527, I became the tutor of their daughter, the later Queen Mary Tudor, or Bloody Mary as she would later be called. I was forced to leave England in 1528 after choosing Catherine’s side when Henry tried to divorce her. I returned to Bruges and was buried in the <strong>Saint Donatian’s Cathedral (link to Saint Donatian’s Cathedral)</strong> in 1540.</p>',
                'description_c' => NULL,
                'created_at' => '2021-05-22 13:00:04',
                'updated_at' => '2021-05-22 13:00:04',
                'deleted_at' => NULL,
                'url' => NULL,
            ),
            21 => 
            array (
                'id' => 22,
                'name' => 'Church of Our Lady',
                'address' => 'Mariastraat',
                'lat' => '51.204761255894674',
                'lng' => '3.224398140494436',
                'description_a' => '<p>With a height of 115.6 meters, the Church of Our Lady is the second tallest brick tower in the world.</p>',
            'description_b' => '<p>The first records of a church on this site go back to the end of the 9th century. Around 1230, the old church was demolished to begin construction on a completely new church, which was finally completed two hundred years later. The monumental church holds an even more impressive interior. As the last duchess of the Burgundy dynasty you’ll find my tomb inside, flanked by that of my father, Charles The Bold, as well as <strong>Peter Longneck\'s (link to swan legend) </strong>funerary monument.&nbsp;</p><p>The highlight of the church is the statue of the Madonna with Child by Michelangelo, the only sculpture by the Italian master to leave Italy during his lifetime. The statue was ordered by two wealthy cloth merchants from Bruges, who donated it to the church in 1514. It has been stolen twice over the course of history. In 1794, French revolutionaries took it with them to Paris, where it stayed for 22 years until it was recovered after Napoleon’s defeat. It was stolen a second time by the German army during the Second World War, but it was retrieved a year later in a salt mine in Austria by a group of officers called the Monuments Men, under the command of George Clooney and Matt Damon.</p>',
                'description_c' => NULL,
                'created_at' => '2021-05-22 13:06:19',
                'updated_at' => '2021-05-22 13:06:19',
                'deleted_at' => NULL,
                'url' => NULL,
            ),
            22 => 
            array (
                'id' => 23,
                'name' => 'Saint Bonifacius Bridge',
                'address' => 'Groeninge 6',
                'lat' => '51.20491538568519',
                'lng' => '3.2253582956365197',
                'description_a' => '<p>The Saint Bonifacius Bridge, or the Lovers Bridge as it is often called, is one of the most picturesque spots in Bruges.</p>',
            'description_b' => '<p>It may look very romantic, but it is actually made with recycled tombstones belonging to the former graveyard of the church. You can still spot some inscriptions on the stones if you look closely. Even though it looks ancient, it is one of the youngest bridges in the city and dates from the early 20th century.&nbsp;</p><p>From the 19th century onwards, as tourism started to develop, the city administrators invested heavily in restoring the medieval look and feel of Bruges. Instead of demolishing old buildings, they chose to restore the historical heritage and supplement it with neo-Gothic elements. Much of the new architecture from that period was also carried out in a neo-Gothic style, including this bridge. The man largely responsible for the Gothic Revival of Bruges was a local architect named Louis Delascenserie, who renovated many of the historical buildings, like the <strong>Gruuthuse Palace (link to Gruuthuse Palace)</strong> next door, and added many new ones, such as the <strong>Provincial Palace (link to Provincial Palace)</strong> on the main square. So you might say that Bruges is as much a medieval city as it is a romantic ode to the Middle Ages.</p>',
                'description_c' => NULL,
                'created_at' => '2021-05-22 13:13:21',
                'updated_at' => '2021-05-22 13:13:21',
                'deleted_at' => NULL,
                'url' => NULL,
            ),
            23 => 
            array (
                'id' => 24,
                'name' => 'Smallest Gothic windows',
                'address' => 'Dijver 17',
                'lat' => '51.20496791931373',
                'lng' => '3.2251950862056624',
            'description_a' => '<p>On the backside of the Gruuthuse palace (link to Gruuthuse Palace), you can spot the smallest Gothic windows in Europe.</p>',
                'description_b' => '<p>The windows, with typical Gothic ornamentation and stained glass, were used by the family to spy on the building next to the bridge, which functioned as a toll house. Since the Gruuthuse family had a large vested interest in trade activities in Bruges, the windows thus served as medieval CCTV cameras, making sure that not a single trader detracted from his obligations.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>',
                'description_c' => NULL,
                'created_at' => '2021-05-22 13:15:20',
                'updated_at' => '2021-05-22 13:15:20',
                'deleted_at' => NULL,
                'url' => NULL,
            ),
            24 => 
            array (
                'id' => 25,
                'name' => 'Groeninge Museum',
                'address' => 'Dijver 12',
                'lat' => '51.205237653227734',
                'lng' => '3.226666555872564',
                'description_a' => '<p>The excellent Groeninge museum provides a varied overview of the history of Belgian visual art.&nbsp;</p>',
                'description_b' => '<p>The museum is renowned for its top-class paintings by Flemish primitives such as myself, Jan van Eyck, but also Rogier Van Der Weyden, Hans Memling and Gerard David. Moreover, the museum contains works by Pieter Brueghel the Younger and Hieronymus Bosch. Many of these masters came from the Low Countries and worked in Bruges to complete assignments for wealthy patrons. Several of the paintings here are regarded as milestones of European art, like my work Virgin and Child with Canon Joris Van der Paele. Using the oil paint technique that I perfected myself, my painting was so realistic that modern dermatologists were able to decipher which type of skin disease Joris Van der Paele was suffering from and determine his cause of death.</p><p>More recent works by Belgian artists are also on display here. From Ensor and Permeke to Van de Woestyne and, of course, René Magritte, this museum has got all the potential to blow your mind. Don’t forget to get the audio guide to discover the impressive collection in more depth!&nbsp;</p>',
                'description_c' => NULL,
                'created_at' => '2021-05-22 13:22:56',
                'updated_at' => '2021-05-22 15:06:18',
                'deleted_at' => NULL,
                'url' => NULL,
            ),
            25 => 
            array (
                'id' => 26,
                'name' => 'Rosary Quai',
                'address' => 'Rozenhoedkaai',
                'lat' => '51.20707915333215',
                'lng' => '3.227490351362369',
                'description_a' => '<p>For centuries, this corner was named the salt dike. The earliest mention of this name dates back to 1390, when it was used as a docking station for ships carrying salt.</p>',
                'description_b' => '<p>Since the 18th century it has been named the Rozenhoedkaai or Rosary Quay, because of the various market stalls along the water that sold rosaries here. Not surprisingly, this quay is the most photographed spot in town. From the corner, you have a beautiful view over the inner city, the river and the Belfry.&nbsp;</p><p>In the movie In Bruges, an action scene was shot here that takes place in the hotel on the other side of the river. The film stars Ralph Fiennes, Brendan Gleeson and Colin Farrell, but the real star is of course the magnificent city of Bruges.&nbsp;</p>',
                'description_c' => NULL,
                'created_at' => '2021-05-22 13:25:52',
                'updated_at' => '2021-05-22 13:25:52',
                'deleted_at' => NULL,
                'url' => NULL,
            ),
            26 => 
            array (
                'id' => 27,
                'name' => 'Tanner’s Square',
                'address' => 'Huidenvettersplein',
                'lat' => '51.20750825955307',
                'lng' => '3.2278700845226758',
                'description_a' => '<p>This cosy square is named after the huidenvetters or tanners, who operated their business here.&nbsp;</p>',
            'description_b' => '<p>The tanners turned animal skins into leather using products like oil, fat and urine, which made it a rather smelly affair. If you look closely, you’ll find a statue of a guy turning up his nose on the wall in the corner of the square. That’s me!</p><p>The smell became so bad that the city forced the tanners to move their trade elsewhere. I was finally freed from their horrific stench, but not for long. Soon after the tanners left, a fish market was installed on the square. All the fish that had not been sold on the regular <strong>fish market (link to Fish market)</strong> after three days, was sold here to the poor. As you can imagine, my situation hadn’t exactly improved. Luckily for me, today the square is used for drinking and dining only.</p>',
                'description_c' => NULL,
                'created_at' => '2021-05-22 13:36:21',
                'updated_at' => '2021-05-22 15:06:28',
                'deleted_at' => NULL,
                'url' => NULL,
            ),
            27 => 
            array (
                'id' => 28,
                'name' => 'Fish Market',
                'address' => 'Vismarkt',
                'lat' => '51.207915462991785',
                'lng' => '3.228327753582498',
                'description_a' => '<p>At first, fish was sold on one of the corners of the main square, but as the townspeople complained about the stench, the fishmongers were forced to move here.</p>',
            'description_b' => '<p>When I was young, I came here regularly to steal some fish. In those days, fresh sea fish was a delicacy that only the rich could afford. Fish that had not been sold after a few days, was offered to the less affluent citizens in a second <strong>fish market (link to Tanner’s square)</strong> just around the corner.&nbsp;</p><p>The covered arcade dates back to 1821 and was specifically erected for the purpose of selling fish. Fresh fish is still on sale here every morning from Wednesday to Saturday. From the fish market it’s only a short walk to the <strong>Burg square (link to Burg square)</strong>, the birthplace of the city, via the gold trimmed portal of the palace of the <strong>Liberty of Bruges (link to Liberty of Bruges)</strong>.</p>',
                'description_c' => NULL,
                'created_at' => '2021-05-22 13:38:25',
                'updated_at' => '2021-05-22 15:06:43',
                'deleted_at' => NULL,
                'url' => NULL,
            ),
            28 => 
            array (
                'id' => 29,
                'name' => 'Bear Statue',
                'address' => 'Burg 11a',
                'lat' => '51.208419089865856',
                'lng' => '3.2272997415213527',
                'description_a' => '<p>The symbol of Bruges is the brown bear, who is considered to be the oldest inhabitant of the city and can be seen above the entrance to the gold-trimmed Liberty of Bruges.</p>',
            'description_b' => '<p>Back in the 9th century, our region was terrorised&nbsp;not only by Vikings, but also by a fearsome bear. On my way here with my fiancée Judith, daughter of the French king, I was attacked by the enormous bear on the outskirts of Bruges. My entourage, who knew all too well the fame of the beast, immediately fled the scene. Left on my own to defend myself and my bride-to-be, I got involved in a fierce battle with the bear. As the ferocious animal stood up on its back legs to attack me, I jumped forward with my lance and pierced the bear to a tree.&nbsp;</p><p>Back in Bruges, the story of my heroic behaviour circulated quickly. When I was inaugurated as the first margrave of Flanders, the people of Bruges donated a carved, upright bear to me, which has since become the symbol of the city. Henceforward, they named me Baldwin Iron Arm in reference to my strength and bravery. You can find my statue on the facade of the <strong>city hall (link to city hall)</strong>, holding my shield and my iron arm.</p>',
                'description_c' => NULL,
                'created_at' => '2021-05-22 13:47:33',
                'updated_at' => '2021-05-22 15:06:57',
                'deleted_at' => NULL,
                'url' => NULL,
            ),
            29 => 
            array (
                'id' => 30,
                'name' => 'City Hall',
                'address' => 'Burg 12',
                'lat' => '51.20833489046114',
                'lng' => '3.227099959712302',
                'description_a' => '<p>The city hall of Bruges is one of the oldest in the Low Countries and replaces a stone fortress that has stood here since the 9th century.&nbsp;</p>',
                'description_b' => '<p>After I married Judith, daughter of the French king, in December 862, I was granted the rulership over these swampy lands, an area regularly flooded by the sea. That’s why it was named Flanders, derived from the Germanic word <i>flauma </i>or flood. When I established the County of Flanders, I built this castle to protect the inhabitants from the Normans. My successors built a prison and church next to it, and construction on the city hall began in 1376.&nbsp;</p><p>The Gothic facade of the town hall is adorned with a large number of statues depicting biblical figures and rulers of Flanders. My statue, holding a shield and my iron arm, can be seen on the bottom row. You can also see the coat of arms of the towns subordinate to the rule of Bruges. Inside, you can visit the lavishly decorated Gothic Hall, with its vaulted ceiling and painted walls depicting the history of the city. The monumental town hall has been the city’s seat of power for more than six hundred years.</p>',
                'description_c' => NULL,
                'created_at' => '2021-05-22 13:54:52',
                'updated_at' => '2021-05-22 13:54:52',
                'deleted_at' => NULL,
                'url' => NULL,
            ),
            30 => 
            array (
                'id' => 31,
                'name' => 'Saint Donatian’s Church',
                'address' => 'Burg',
                'lat' => '51.20880367438334',
                'lng' => '3.226983723017858',
                'description_a' => '<p>Built in Carolingian style by my successor Arnulf I around 950, the Saint Donatian\'s Church stood across the city hall for nearly nine hundred years.</p>',
            'description_b' => '<p>For a long time, it was the biggest church in the city. The church was the final resting place of many counts and countesses, as well as notable figures like <strong>Juan Luis Vives (link to Juan Luis Vives)</strong> and <strong>Jan van Eyck (link to Jan van Eyck)</strong>. In 1127, while Count Charles the Good was praying in the church, he was <strong>murdered (link to Oldest Wall) </strong>on the spot in a confrontation between him and the emerging trade elites. This event culminated in a huge political crisis and the intervention of the French king, who had the conspirators thrown from the highest tower in the city. In the widespread chaos that followed, the first <strong>city ramparts (link to Oldest wall)</strong> were constructed and the first alderman’s college was installed in Bruges.&nbsp;</p><p>The Saint Donatian\'s Church became a cathedral following the installation of the first Bishop of Bruges in 1562, but was demolished in 1799 in the wake of the French Revolution. The former site of the cathedral is now occupied by the Crowne Plaza Hotel. The foundations of the cathedral were uncovered in 1955 and can be visited for free in the hotel\'s cellars.</p>',
                'description_c' => NULL,
                'created_at' => '2021-05-22 13:58:21',
                'updated_at' => '2021-05-22 13:58:21',
                'deleted_at' => NULL,
                'url' => NULL,
            ),
            31 => 
            array (
                'id' => 32,
                'name' => 'Legend of the Gilded Dragon',
                'address' => 'Burg',
                'lat' => '51.20888673511381',
                'lng' => '3.2267803088122795',
                'description_a' => '<p>The top of the Saint Donatian\'s Church on the Burg square was once crowned by a statue of a gilded dragon that was considered to be the protector of the city.&nbsp;</p>',
            'description_b' => '<p>However, it failed to protect the citizens from the people of Ghent at the end of the 14th century, when the Ghentians rebelled against the Flemish count and raided Bruges. The cowards of Ghent chose to attack the day after the city of Bruges had held its yearly <strong>Procession of the Holy Blood (link to Basilica of the Holy Blood)</strong>. While the citizens of Bruges were exhausted and hungover from a day of festivities, the army of Ghent managed to breach the walls and enter the city.</p><p>Once inside, the soldiers of Ghent started plundering all around. While they were on the Burg square celebrating their victory over Bruges, they spotted the magnificent gilded dragon on top of the church and decided to take it back to Ghent as a trophy. They gathered a donkey and a cart to transport the dragon, but when they tried to leave, the donkey refused to move. It had never ventured outside the confines of the city before, and it didn’t plan on changing that. The stubborn animal didn’t budge, until a gentle soul came up with the idea to burn out the donkey’s eyes with a candle. Once blinded, the donkey crossed the gate and left Bruges with the gilded dragon loaded in the back.&nbsp;</p><p>Hence, we named this street the Blind Donkey Street, in commemoration of the heroic donkey that tried to save our dragon. Still today, much to the regret of the people of Bruges, you can find our gilded dragon on top of the Belfry of Ghent. Anyone who manages to steal it back can expect a hero’s welcome in Bruges!</p>',
                'description_c' => NULL,
                'created_at' => '2021-05-22 14:05:42',
                'updated_at' => '2021-05-22 14:05:42',
                'deleted_at' => NULL,
                'url' => NULL,
            ),
            32 => 
            array (
                'id' => 33,
                'name' => 'Basilica of the Holy Blood',
                'address' => 'Burg 13',
                'lat' => '51.20815471690308',
                'lng' => '3.226542070779024',
                'description_a' => '<p>Next to the city hall is the Basilica of the Holy Blood, one of the oldest buildings in the city.</p>',
                'description_b' => '<p>The basilica consists of an upper and a lower chapel. The lower chapel is constructed in Romanesque style and is dedicated to Saint Basil. It was built in the 12th century by Count Thierry of Alsace as a private chapel to the count’s residence. The upper chapel dates back to the 15th century and is built in Gothic style, but has undergone multiple neo-Gothic restorations since. Both are free to visit and are remarkably beautiful, so make sure to check them out!</p><p>The Relic of the Holy Blood, said to have been brought to Bruges by the crusaders and believed to contain the blood of Christ, is kept in the upper part of the basilica. Every year on Ascension Day, the relic is carried around the city in the famous Procession of the Holy Blood. First held in 1304, it counts as one of the oldest ongoing processions in the world and is listed as UNESCO Intangible Cultural Heritage. The church received the status of basilica in 1923 and the shrine is accessible daily for worship.</p>',
                'description_c' => NULL,
                'created_at' => '2021-05-22 14:08:39',
                'updated_at' => '2021-05-22 14:10:44',
                'deleted_at' => NULL,
                'url' => NULL,
            ),
            33 => 
            array (
                'id' => 34,
                'name' => 'Manor of the Liberty of Bruges',
                'address' => 'Burg 11',
                'lat' => '51.20856448452279',
                'lng' => '3.2273759433424614',
                'description_a' => '<p>The Manor of the Liberty of Bruges, rebuilt in the 18th century in classicist style, was for centuries the administrative center of the Liberty of Bruges, an autonomous region encompassing the countryside around Bruges.</p>',
                'description_b' => '<p>At the end of the 14th century, this wealthy, agricultural area was added as the fourth member to the States of Flanders, which gave it decision-making power in administrative matters in the County of Flanders alongside the major cities of Ghent, Bruges and Ypres.</p><p>After the Liberty of Bruges was dissolved in 1795, the building served for two hundred years as a court of justice, as evidenced by the gold-trimmed statue of Lady Justice on the facade of the Old Civil Registry. The magnificent registry, in the corner of the Burg next to the town hall, dates from the 16th century and is a rare example of Renaissance architecture in Bruges. Inside, you can still visit the old alderman\'s college of the Liberty of Bruges, which is included in a visit to the city hall. Nowadays, the city council\'s administration and the city archives are located here.</p>',
                'description_c' => NULL,
                'created_at' => '2021-05-22 14:18:11',
                'updated_at' => '2021-05-22 14:18:11',
                'deleted_at' => NULL,
                'url' => NULL,
            ),
            34 => 
            array (
                'id' => 35,
                'name' => 'House Ter Beurze',
                'address' => 'Vlamingstraat 35',
                'lat' => '51.211212205423685',
                'lng' => '3.2239339209687468',
                'description_a' => '<p>Here we are at the cradle of modern capitalism, one of the first stock exchanges in the world.&nbsp;</p>',
            'description_b' => '<p>Next to the old bourse you\'ll find the <strong>Venetian Lodge (link to Venetian nation house)</strong>, the former headquarters of the Venetian traders. It is no coincidence that the bourse and the Venetian Lodge are located next to one another, because it was in Venice that modern banking and Western capitalism developed in the 13th century. In my days, thanks to the booming cloth industry, there were a lot of trading activities between the Flemish and the Italians, especially from Genoa, Venice and Florence, and their trading houses were located around this square.</p><p>As a salt trader, I paid with salt in exchange for coins or goods, which was common practice in the old days and gave origin to the word salary. Other products like tobacco leaves, copper or cloth were also accepted as currency. Trade was booming and merchants started to gather a lot of wealth, so we needed a place where we could safely store our wealth and have access to it whenever and wherever we needed. That’s how the first modern banks were created, most notably by the Medici family in my hometown of Florence, who early on established one of their <strong>main branches (link to Bladelin Court)</strong> here in Bruges.&nbsp;</p><p>Soon, traders began receiving a value paper, an IOU, as a proof of deposit. It wasn’t long before we would use these securities as money and started trading them with each other. This marked the start of paper money in Europe and the trading community in Bruges became one of the early adopters of this new financial instrument. This may very well explain why Bruges would become known as the Venice of the North: not simply because of its breath-taking beauty and its many canals, but primarily because the city was the financial centre of the north.</p><p>To regulate the trade in paper bonds and set the exchange rates, one of the world’s first exchange markets developed in Bruges. It was a tavern that belonged to the local Van der Buerse family and was frequented by both local and foreign traders. As a result, the family’s name is still used to denominate a stock exchange in many different languages: beurs, bourse, Börse, bolsa, birža. Countless foreign traders, all with their own customs, languages and currencies, came to the tavern to trade bills of exchange with each other, and every day a bell would mark the beginning and end of the trade activities. The original tavern dates back to 1285, the current building was constructed in 1453.</p>',
                'description_c' => NULL,
                'created_at' => '2021-05-22 14:26:19',
                'updated_at' => '2021-05-22 14:26:19',
                'deleted_at' => NULL,
                'url' => NULL,
            ),
            35 => 
            array (
                'id' => 36,
                'name' => 'Venetian Nation House',
                'address' => 'Vlamingstraat 37',
                'lat' => '51.2112753240644',
                'lng' => '3.2239908549731826',
                'description_a' => '<p>A nation house was a permanent commercial and diplomatic representation of foreign traders in the city.&nbsp;</p>',
                'description_b' => '<p>As Bruges was a prominent international port, it attracted traders from all over Europe. Foreign merchants from the same city or country organised themselves in nation houses: communal offices that were used as consulates, meeting rooms and warehouses.&nbsp;</p><p>The Venetian nation house moved here in 1397. The Italians mainly brought textiles, sugar, citrus fruits, jewellery and spices from the Far East, and usually returned with a shipload of Flemish cloth.</p>',
                'description_c' => NULL,
                'created_at' => '2021-05-22 14:28:31',
                'updated_at' => '2021-05-22 14:28:31',
                'deleted_at' => NULL,
                'url' => NULL,
            ),
            36 => 
            array (
                'id' => 37,
                'name' => 'Genovese Nation House',
                'address' => 'Vlamingstraat 33',
                'lat' => '51.211001835783605',
                'lng' => '3.2240102361676133',
                'description_a' => '<p>The Genovese nation house dates from 1399 and was the headquarters of the traders from Genoa until they left the city in 1551.&nbsp;</p>',
                'description_b' => '<p>Above the entrance is a half-relief portraying the fight between Saint George and the dragon. Saint George was the patron of Genoa and the scene is an allegory of the battle between good and evil. Nowadays, the former Genovese nation house is home to the Fries Museum.</p>',
                'description_c' => NULL,
                'created_at' => '2021-05-22 14:30:31',
                'updated_at' => '2021-05-22 14:30:31',
                'deleted_at' => NULL,
                'url' => NULL,
            ),
            37 => 
            array (
                'id' => 38,
                'name' => 'Florentine Nation House',
                'address' => 'Academiestraat 1',
                'lat' => '51.21127020775887',
                'lng' => '3.224190921232859',
                'description_a' => '<p>This corner house dates from the 13th century and became the headquarters of my fellow Florentine traders around 1420.</p>',
                'description_b' => '<p>On the side wall you can find a copper plate with some verses from La Divina Commedia by the Florentine poet Dante Alighieri: ‘Like the Flemings between Wissant and Bruges who, in fear of the flood which advances in their direction, raise a dyke so the sea would flee.’ Nowadays, it accommodates a restaurant with a very appropriate name.</p>',
                'description_c' => NULL,
                'created_at' => '2021-05-22 14:32:08',
                'updated_at' => '2021-05-22 14:32:08',
                'deleted_at' => NULL,
                'url' => NULL,
            ),
            38 => 
            array (
                'id' => 39,
                'name' => 'Wooden House',
                'address' => 'Kortewinkel 2 + Genthof 7',
                'lat' => '51.21230186305492 + 51.21206665788987',
                'lng' => '3.2235034988172955 + 3.2260996711606165',
                'description_a' => '<p>In the early Middle Ages, houses were built in wood, like this one, and covered by straw roofs.&nbsp;</p>',
                'description_b' => '<p>When Bruges became more populated, houses were often built right next to one another without a set plan. In some cases the only way to enter one’s house was by going through a neighbour’s house, which often led to hilarious disputes.&nbsp;</p><p>Over time, more and more houses were built in stone and today, only two original wooden houses remain in Bruges. Both can be found in the German quarter of the city and date from the 15th century. Both houses contain three sides made of stone, with the facade built in wood. Stone walls on the sides prevented a fire from spreading to the neighbouring house, while the facade was less important to be fireproof. In May 1616, the city issued a law prohibiting the renovation or construction of wooden buildings with the aim to reduce the risk of fire.</p><p>You can see how the different floors of the building overhang each other. This has multiple advantages: it protects the facade from the rain and it increases the living space. What’s more, it was a form of tax evasion as each house was taxed according to its size at street level.&nbsp;</p><p>The inside was a big open space that was often shared between several families. The floors were covered with straw or reed and the families would huddle together around a fireplace. In case it was owned by a rich family - say, a German banker - the ground floor would be used as a business premise. The living quarters would be on the second and third floor and the server’s quarter in the attic. The basement was generally used as storage space.</p>',
                'description_c' => NULL,
                'created_at' => '2021-05-22 14:39:51',
                'updated_at' => '2021-05-22 14:39:51',
                'deleted_at' => NULL,
                'url' => NULL,
            ),
            39 => 
            array (
                'id' => 40,
                'name' => 'Bear of the Lodge',
                'address' => 'Academiestraat 14',
                'lat' => '51.211572424164224',
                'lng' => '3.225344829877544',
                'description_a' => '<p>The Bear of the Lodge is located on the side of the Burgher’s Lodge, a meeting place for the most affluent members of the Bruges society.</p>',
            'description_b' => '<p>The bear was the mascot of the Society of the White Bear, an association that was devoted to organising tournaments and jousts around Bruges in the 14th and 15th century. The other statues on the facade represent notable figures from the history of the city.</p><p>The bear is the symbol of Bruges and is considered to be the oldest inhabitant of the city. Back in the 9th century, our region was not only ravaged by Vikings, but also by a large bear that terrorised the area. When Baldwin was on his way to Bruges with his fiancée Judith, the daughter of the French king, he was attacked by the bear just outside the city. Baldwin’s entourage, who knew all too well the fame of the beast, immediately fled the scene. Left on his own to protect himself and his bride-to-be, he got involved in a fierce battle with the bear. As the ferocious animal stood up on its back legs to attack him, Baldwin jumped forward with his lance and pierced the bear to a tree.&nbsp;</p><p>Back in Bruges, the story of his heroic behaviour circulated quickly. When he was inaugurated as the first margrave of Flanders, the people of Bruges donated a carved, upright bear to him, which has since become the symbol of the city. Henceforward, they named him Baldwin Iron Arm (link to city hall), in reference to his strength and bravery.&nbsp;</p>',
                'description_c' => NULL,
                'created_at' => '2021-05-22 14:49:18',
                'updated_at' => '2021-05-22 14:49:18',
                'deleted_at' => NULL,
                'url' => NULL,
            ),
            40 => 
            array (
                'id' => 41,
                'name' => 'Statue of Jan van Eyck',
                'address' => 'Jan van Eyckplein',
                'lat' => '51.211651416022164',
                'lng' => '3.226062138875309',
                'description_a' => '<p>My name is Jan van Eyck. Born around 1390, I’m considered one of the greatest masters of Flemish art with paintings that almost perfectly resembled the real world.&nbsp;</p>',
            'description_b' => '<p>The detail of my work was spectacular, if I may say so myself! The shadows, refined robes, transparency of water, glow of jewels and perspective are still admired by modern painters today. My handling of oil paint was so exquisite and my ability to keep the colour’s saturation and brightness was so remarkable, that many regard me as the father of oil painting. Besides mastering the art of painting, I also excelled in the field of politics, theology and physics.&nbsp;</p><p>As court painter, ambassador and close advisor to the Burgundian Duke Philip the Good, I was involved in some of the duke’s secret missions. When he had plans to marry Isabella, the daughter of the Portugese king, he sent me all the way to Lisbon to paint her portrait. It took me four months to complete the mission, but it was worth it, because he eventually decided to marry her based on the portrait I produced. The couple had three children, of whom only their son Charles survived childhood. Philip also fathered at least eighteen bastard children with his many mistresses - I know of at least thirty. Luckily, he didn’t ask me to paint their portraits too.</p><p>Unfortunately, only twenty of my works have been preserved today. My most famous work is the Ghent Altarpiece, which you can admire in Saint Bavo\'s Cathedral in Ghent. Here in Bruges, where I lived from 1432 until my death in 1441, you can still find two of my works in the <strong>Groeninge museum (link to Groeninge)</strong>. I was buried in the <strong>Saint Donatian’s Church (link to Saint Donatian’s Church) </strong>on the Burg square.</p><p>Today, the canal disappears under my feet, but in the Middle Ages boats could continue all the way to the <strong>Water Hall (link to Water Hall)</strong> on the Market square.</p>',
                'description_c' => NULL,
                'created_at' => '2021-05-22 14:54:02',
                'updated_at' => '2021-05-22 14:54:02',
                'deleted_at' => NULL,
                'url' => NULL,
            ),
            41 => 
            array (
                'id' => 42,
                'name' => 'Toll House',
                'address' => 'Jan van Eyckplein 2',
                'lat' => '51.21172398541039',
                'lng' => '3.225529597781362',
                'description_a' => '<p>This building served as the toll house of the city, back when this square was the bustling harbour of Bruges.&nbsp;</p>',
            'description_b' => '<p>Ships from all over the continent docked here to load and unload. A big crane stood not far from here, powered by so-called crane children, who had to run around in its wheels like hamsters.&nbsp;</p><p>There were two types of toll: a small toll, levied on local goods at the <strong>city gates (link to City gates)</strong>, and a big toll, levied on long distance trade at the ports. Once unloaded, the goods were taken to the weighing station of the toll house, where they were taxed according to their weight. The building was renovated in 1478 by Pieter of Luxembourg, a knight of the <strong>Order of the Golden Fleece (link to Gruuthuse museum)</strong>, whose family held the right to levy the big toll. The coat of arms of the Luxembourg family can still be seen above the entrance.&nbsp;</p><p>The toll house was used for a long time as a library and provincial information centre.</p>',
                'description_c' => NULL,
                'created_at' => '2021-05-22 14:57:42',
                'updated_at' => '2021-05-22 14:57:42',
                'deleted_at' => NULL,
                'url' => NULL,
            ),
            42 => 
            array (
                'id' => 43,
                'name' => 'Guild House of the Dock Workers',
                'address' => 'Spanjaardstraat 2',
                'lat' => '51.21158704310192',
                'lng' => '3.225425662071788',
                'description_a' => '<p>To the left of the toll house is the guild house of the dock workers. It was called <i>‘t Pijndershuisje</i> or the house of pain, as a reference to the heavy labour of these men.</p>',
                'description_b' => '<p>The little statues on the facade of the building illustrate their strenuous trade. This was the base from where the dock workers operated, carrying the cargo from the boats to the warehouses located around the square. The guild house is the narrowest house in Bruges and dates back to 1470. The statues above the entrance represent Saint George, Saint John the Baptist, Saint Ambrose and Saint John the Evangelist.</p>',
                'description_c' => NULL,
                'created_at' => '2021-05-22 15:04:22',
                'updated_at' => '2021-05-22 15:04:22',
                'deleted_at' => NULL,
                'url' => NULL,
            ),
            43 => 
            array (
                'id' => 44,
                'name' => 'Burgher’s Lodge',
                'address' => 'Academiestraat 14',
                'lat' => '51.211449261609445',
                'lng' => '3.2252781405783377',
                'description_a' => '<p>The Poortersloge or Burgher’s Lodge is the remarkable building with the small tower. Built between the 14th and 15th century, it functioned as a meeting place for the commercial elite at a time when this district was the hub of international trade.</p>',
            'description_b' => '<p>The building is located right in front of the harbour, where ships stopped before entering the city centre. From high up the tower, the traders could spot the boats approaching from a distance.&nbsp;</p><p>The Poortersloge also served as the meeting space for the Society of the White Bear, an association devoted to organising tournaments and jousts around Bruges from 1320 to 1489. The mascot of the society, the <strong>Bear of the Lodge (link to Bear of the Lodge)</strong>, can be seen on the facade. Later, the building served as the academy for Fine Arts and the house of the State Archives. These days it is used mainly as an exhibition space.</p>',
                'description_c' => NULL,
                'created_at' => '2021-05-22 15:12:28',
                'updated_at' => '2021-05-22 15:12:28',
                'deleted_at' => NULL,
                'url' => NULL,
            ),
