            46 => 
            array (
                'id' => 47,
                'name' => 'Jerusalem Chapel',
                'address' => 'Peperstraat 3',
                'lat' => '51.21263476176783',
                'lng' => '3.233829238617925',
                'description_a' => '<p>The Jerusalem Chapel of Bruges was inspired by the Church of the Holy Sepulchre in Jerusalem, the site where Jesus Christ is believed to be buried and resurrected.</p>',
                'description_b' => '<p>The Jerusalem Chapel was built as a prestige project in the 15th century by the Adornes family, a wealthy family of Genovese merchants. Some of its members had previously made a pilgrimage to Jerusalem and decided to copy elements of the original church to build their own version in Bruges. Nowadays it’s impossible to compare both, since the church in Jerusalem was destroyed by a fire in the 16th century.</p><p>During the construction of this church, the family also included a replica of the tomb of Jesus Christ. Legend has it that when the builders attempted to place the cover stone on the replica of the Holy Grave, the stone cracked in half. A year later, when they tried it a second time with a new stone, it cracked again in exactly the same way. It was at that moment that the family decided to travel back to Jerusalem to take another look at the Holy Grave. When they arrived on site, they were amazed to see that the same crack also featured on the original stone.</p><p>I don’t know if this story is true or not, but I do know for a fact that members of the Adornes family travelled to the Holy Land twice in a short period of time. Historical records of those journeys have been preserved and the top of the church still carries the cross of Jerusalem. The church has always remained private property in the hands of the same family, which saved it from the destruction caused by religious revolts. The church is part of a museum and is definitely worth a visit.</p>',
                'description_c' => NULL,
                'created_at' => '2021-06-08 11:54:57',
                'updated_at' => '2021-06-08 11:54:57',
                'deleted_at' => NULL,
                'url' => NULL,
            ),
            47 => 
            array (
                'id' => 48,
                'name' => 'Wind mills',
                'address' => 'Kruisvest 3 + Kruisvest 5 + Kruisvest',
                'lat' => '51.21553932520028 + 51.213886061967884 + 51.21774358382097',
                'lng' => '3.2381367687852594 + 3.2390916352044896 + 3.2363986973234473',
                'description_a' => '<p>For centuries, about 25 to 30 windmills stood along the city walls. They produced the flour needed to make the bread and beer to feed the growing population.&nbsp;</p>',
                'description_b' => '<p>During the 19th century, the windmills were gradually replaced by steam mills and became obsolete. Today, only four mills remain and can be found between the Dampoort and the Kruispoort. From the top of their hills, you can get some of the best views of the skyline of the city.</p>',
                'description_c' => NULL,
                'created_at' => '2021-06-08 12:00:23',
                'updated_at' => '2021-06-08 12:00:23',
                'deleted_at' => NULL,
                'url' => NULL,
            ),
            48 => 
            array (
                'id' => 49,
                'name' => 'Cross Gate',
                'address' => 'Langestraat 191',
                'lat' => '51.21271623736785',
                'lng' => '3.240128221914558',
                'description_a' => '<p>One of the main tasks of any city is to provide security for its citizens. All throughout the Middle Ages, the best protection was offered by a moat and a stone wall.</p>',
            'description_b' => '<p>Parts of the city were surrounded by a wall, including a series of defence towers and city gates. After the gates closed in the evening, nobody could enter or leave the city without permission. Merchants who wanted to bring goods inside were obliged to pay a <strong>toll (link to Toll house)</strong> at the gate. To scare people with bad intentions, heads or limbs of convicted criminals were often hung above the entrance.&nbsp;</p><p>In Bruges, several canals were dug manually in the 12th and 13th centuries to protect the city in addition to the city walls. They had to be constantly guarded, especially during winter, when the canals could freeze over and make it easy for enemies to cross. For that reason, guards were obliged to break up the ice from time to time.</p><p>The decline of Bruges from the 16th century onwards caused the city walls to be torn down, but four of the medieval city gates still remain. The Kruispoort or Cross Gate was built around 1300 and is a fine example of medieval military architecture. The Kruispoort has been witness to many historical arrivals: Charles V, Napoleon and the German army all entered Bruges through this gate.&nbsp;</p>',
                'description_c' => NULL,
                'created_at' => '2021-06-08 12:06:50',
                'updated_at' => '2021-06-08 12:06:50',
                'deleted_at' => NULL,
                'url' => NULL,
            ),
            49 => 
            array (
                'id' => 50,
                'name' => 'Ghent Gate',
                'address' => 'Boninvest 113',
                'lat' => '51.20310298318856',
                'lng' => '3.234530728057936',
                'description_a' => '<p>One of the main tasks of any city is to provide security for its citizens. All throughout the Middle Ages, the best protection was offered by a moat and a stone wall.</p>',
            'description_b' => '<p>Parts of the city were surrounded by a wall, including a series of defence towers and city gates. After the gates closed in the evening, nobody could enter or leave the city without permission. Merchants who wanted to bring goods inside were obliged to pay a toll (link to Toll house) at the gate. To scare people with bad intentions, heads or limbs of convicted criminals were often hung above the entrance.&nbsp;</p><p>In Bruges, several canals were dug manually in the 12th and 13th centuries to protect the city in addition to the city walls. They had to be constantly guarded, especially during winter, when the canals could freeze over and make it easy for enemies to cross. For that reason, guards were obliged to break up the ice from time to time.</p><p>The decline of Bruges from the 16th century onwards caused the city walls to be torn down, but four of the medieval city gates still remain.The Gentpoort or Ghent Gate is one of them and was part of the <strong>second city wall (link to oldest wall)</strong> dating back to 1297.</p>',
                'description_c' => NULL,
                'created_at' => '2021-06-08 12:09:00',
                'updated_at' => '2021-06-08 12:09:00',
                'deleted_at' => NULL,
                'url' => NULL,
            ),
            50 => 
            array (
                'id' => 51,
                'name' => 'Donkey’s Gate',
                'address' => 'Ezelstraat 122',
                'lat' => '51.21509380276847',
                'lng' => '3.216446697621596',
                'description_a' => '<p>One of the main tasks of any city is to provide security for its citizens. All throughout the Middle Ages, the best protection was offered by a moat and a stone wall.</p>',
            'description_b' => '<p>Parts of the city were surrounded by a wall, including a series of defence towers and city gates. After the gates closed in the evening, nobody could enter or leave the city without permission. Merchants who wanted to bring goods inside were obliged to pay a toll (link to Toll house) at the gate. To scare people with bad intentions, heads or limbs of convicted criminals were often hung above the entrance.&nbsp;</p><p>In Bruges, several canals were dug manually in the 12th and 13th centuries to protect the city in addition to the city walls. They had to be constantly guarded, especially during winter, when the canals could freeze over and make it easy for enemies to cross. For that reason, guards were obliged to break up the ice from time to time.</p><p>The decline of Bruges from the 16th century onwards caused the city walls to be torn down, but four of the medieval city gates still remain. The Ezelpoort or Donkey’s Gate is one of them and was part of the <strong>second city wall (link to oldest wall)</strong> dating back to 1297.</p>',
                'description_c' => NULL,
                'created_at' => '2021-06-08 12:11:26',
                'updated_at' => '2021-06-08 12:11:26',
