            51 => 
            array (
                'id' => 52,
                'name' => 'Blacksmith’s Gate',
                'address' => 'Smedenstraat 71',
                'lat' => '51.2046702339494',
                'lng' => '3.212356997621116',
                'description_a' => '<p>The medieval Smedenpoort or Blacksmith’s Gate dates from 1297 and is one of the four remaining city gates of Bruges.</p>',
                'description_b' => '<p>If you look closely at the upper lefthand corner above the arch, you’ll notice a morbid curiosity: a bronzed human skull is affixed to the gate’s yellow brick facade. It is a replica of the skull of an executed traitor, whose head was prominently displayed as a warning to the people.&nbsp;</p><p>For that story, we need to go back to 1691, when hostile French troops had gathered near Bruges. Unable to infiltrate the city’s ramparts, they conspired with a local man named Francois van der Straeten to smuggle a small group of French soldiers inside the city to allow them to open the gate and let the army in. Unfortunately for Francois, the plot was discovered and brought before the city council. Francois van der Straeten was arrested and hanged that same day on June 26, 1691. His head was cut off and hung from an iron pin on the gate to serve as an example. The skull disappeared in the aftermath of the French Revolution and was rediscovered in 1876. The remnants of the original skull are housed in the Archaeological Museum of Bruges, and a bronze replica now adornes the gate.&nbsp;</p>',
                'description_c' => NULL,
                'created_at' => '2021-06-08 12:13:50',
                'updated_at' => '2021-06-08 12:13:50',
                'deleted_at' => NULL,
                'url' => NULL,
            ),
            52 => 
            array (
                'id' => 53,
                'name' => 'Saint Saviour’s Cathedral',
                'address' => 'Sint-Salvatorskoorstraat 8',
                'lat' => '51.205573600345566',
                'lng' => '3.221648737517308',
                'description_a' => '<p>The Saint Saviour’s Cathedral is the oldest parish church of the city. It was founded as a Romanesque chapel in the 9th century and was later converted into a church.</p>',
            'description_b' => '<p>The church has experienced several fires but has always been rebuilt, often with the help of wealthy townspeople. Construction of the present Gothic church began in 1250, though some significant changes have been made over the centuries.&nbsp;</p><p>The Saint Saviour’s Church became a cathedral in 1834 after the destruction of the <strong>Saint Donatian’s Cathedral (link to Saint Donatian’s Church)</strong> on the Burg square. However, because the building\'s external image did not resemble a cathedral - it was much smaller and less imposing than the nearby Church of Our Lady - the tower was made higher and more impressive to adapt to its new role.</p><p>The cathedral is home to several art treasures that were rescued from its demolished predecessor, like the Brussels tapestries or the portrait of the murdered Count <strong>Charles the Good (link to Oldest wall)</strong>. One of the highlights, above the choir, are the coats of arms of the 13th chapter of the <strong>Order of the Golden Fleece (link to Gruuthuse museum)</strong>, which was held here in 1478. The two organs and the treasure chamber, displaying a rich collection of Flemish paintings, are also worth a visit.</p><p>When standing in front of the cathedral, one can clearly notice the difference in street level. The explanation for this is quite simple: because the street layers have been placed on top of one another over time, there is a difference of several meters between the constantly changing street level and that of the cathedral, which has remained the same for centuries.</p>',
                'description_c' => NULL,
                'created_at' => '2021-06-08 12:16:19',
                'updated_at' => '2021-06-08 12:16:19',
                'deleted_at' => NULL,
                'url' => NULL,
            ),
            53 => 
            array (
                'id' => 54,
                'name' => 'Statue of Simon Stevin',
                'address' => 'Simon Stevinplein',
                'lat' => '51.206625315038835',
                'lng' => '3.2227638144531303',
                'description_a' => '<p>Hello there! It’s me: Simon Stevin, the man after whom this square has been named.</p>',
                'description_b' => '<p>I’ll tell you a little bit about myself, but first, come a bit closer. If you look closely at my statue, you might see I am actually standing on an old water pump instead of an ordinary pedestal. Odd no? That’s because for five hundred years this square was home to a giant meat hall, until it was taken down in the early 19th century. The meat hall was the biggest slaughterhouse of the city. Can you imagine the looks of the place? Not to mention the smell?</p><p>So let’s tell you a little bit about myself. I was born in Bruges in 1548 and I turned out to be a pretty good mathematician. I started out my career as an accountant, but I had many other fields of interest, like hydraulic engineering, architecture, urban planning, music theory, linguistics, navigation, physics and astrology. Yes, you can say I was quite the homo universalis. At the age of 33, I moved from Bruges to Leiden to study mathematical sciences. During my studies I met the Dutch Prince Maurits of Nassau, who hired me as his tutor and counsellor.</p><p>As a scientist, I improved many techniques and invented some cool things, like the sail wagon I designed for the prince. The one I am most famous for is my simplification of calculations with fractions by adding a decimal sign, which is either a point or a comma. This means that without me, you wouldn’t be able to count the way you do today. My work inspired Thomas Jefferson to introduce a decimal currency and is the reason why Americans are still paying in dimes today. I died in 1620 as one of the greatest scientists of my time.</p><p>The square that carries my name is an enjoyable place to sit down and have a drink or eat something. To most people, it is known for The Chocolate Line: a world famous chocolate shop with the most creative and bizarre flavour combinations. Have you ever tried white chocolate with basil, sun-dried tomato and olive chutney; almond pralines with fried onions; or milk chocolates with crispy bacon and quinoa? Now is your chance! The man behind this chocolate shop, Dominique Persoone, has been praised as the number one chocolatier in the world and, if you ask me, deserves a statue of his own.</p>',
                'description_c' => NULL,
                'created_at' => '2021-06-08 12:21:55',
                'updated_at' => '2021-06-08 12:21:55',
                'deleted_at' => NULL,
                'url' => NULL,
            ),
            54 => 
            array (
                'id' => 55,
                'name' => 'Zand Square',
                'address' => 'Het Zand',
                'lat' => '51.20514557423234',
                'lng' => '3.2175991308759797',
                'description_a' => '<p>One of the more atypical places within the former city walls of Bruges is known as ‘t Zand.</p>',
                'description_b' => '<p>In the Middle Ages, the square was used for jousts, executions and other festivities, as well as weekly cattle and horse markets. From 1838 the first train station was located here, until the current station just outside the city gates was completed in 1936. Nowadays, the wide open square is still used for fairs and weekly fresh markets on Saturdays. Every once in a while, a giant screen is placed here to display the superiority of the Red Devils, the Belgian national football team.&nbsp;</p><p>The big red building is the concert hall, renowned for its exquisite sound quality. This international music and arts centre offers the very best in contemporary dance and classical music. The impressive Concert Auditorium holds 1289 seats and is used for large concerts and shows, while the smaller Chamber Music Hall is designed for more intimate events. The concert building was completed in 2002, when Bruges was crowned the European Capital of Culture. From its rooftop, visitors can enjoy a panoramic city view.</p>',
                'description_c' => NULL,
                'created_at' => '2021-06-08 12:24:36',
                'updated_at' => '2021-06-08 12:24:36',
                'deleted_at' => NULL,
                'url' => NULL,
            ),
            55 => 
            array (
                'id' => 56,
                'name' => 'Queen Astrid Park',
                'address' => 'Koningin Astridpark',
                'lat' => '51.206201841553074',
                'lng' => '3.2312311399484432',
                'description_a' => '<p>One of the rare green treasures within the city walls is the Queen Astrid Park.</p>',
                'description_b' => '<p>For more than five centuries, this beautiful green oasis was the garden of the monastery of the Recollect friars. After the French revolutionaries got hold of the government and dissolved all religious communities in 1796, the monastery was torn down and the gardens fell into private hands.&nbsp;</p><p>The city bought the land in the middle of the 19th century with the intention to build a prison on its grounds, but eventually decided to turn it into a public park. Part of the site was used for the construction of the Saint Magdalene’s Church, which nowadays hosts all sorts of cultural events, art projects and even a pop-up coffee bar. At the entrance of the park is L’Estaminet, one of the most authentic and loved bars in Bruges.&nbsp;</p><p>Often referred to as the Botanical Garden by locals, the park was named after the Belgian Queen Astrid following her tragic death due to a car accident in 1935. The tiny lake and colourful kiosk are an ideal place to spend a relaxing afternoon with loved ones.</p>',
                'description_c' => NULL,
                'created_at' => '2021-06-08 12:26:52',
                'updated_at' => '2021-06-08 12:26:52',
                'deleted_at' => NULL,
                'url' => NULL,
            ),
            56 => 
            array (
                'id' => 57,
                'name' => 'Saint Jacob’s Church',
                'address' => 'Sint-Jakobsplein 1',
                'lat' => '51.210508139406095',
                'lng' => '3.2203359625863315',
                'description_a' => '<p>The Saint Jacob’s Church or Saint James’ Church, dedicated to James the Apostle, is located along the camino, the pilgrimage route to Santiago de Compostela in Spain, where the remains of Saint Jacob are believed to be buried.</p>',
            'description_b' => '<p>At the entrance of the church, you can find one of the famous Saint Jacob’s shells that are scattered all over town and were meant to point pilgrims the way.&nbsp;</p><p>The church dedicated to Saint Jacob was the most affluent of the parish churches in Bruges. This Gothic church was founded around 1240 to serve a neighbourhood full of rich traders, bankers and craftsmen, as well as important political figures. In 1459, an ambitious campaign to enlarge the church began as a reflection of the increasing wealth and prestige of its parishioners, which by then included the household of the dukes of Burgundy in the nearby <strong>Prinsenhof (link to Prinsenhof)</strong>. They showered the church with tombs, copper tomb plates, altars and paintings, and many of these art treasures still form part of the Baroque interior today.&nbsp;</p>',
                'description_c' => NULL,
                'created_at' => '2021-06-08 12:29:13',
                'updated_at' => '2021-06-08 12:29:13',
                'deleted_at' => NULL,
                'url' => NULL,
            ),
            57 => 
            array (
                'id' => 58,
                'name' => 'Saint Walburga’s Church',
                'address' => 'Sint-Maartensplein',
                'lat' => '51.2112977142618',
                'lng' => '3.2288535454409697',
                'description_a' => '<p>The Baroque Saint Walburga’s Church is a former Jesuit church located in the old Scottish quarter.</p>',
            'description_b' => '<p>Built on the site of a chapel that is said to have been founded in 745 by Saint Walburga herself, the present church was constructed by Jesuit brother Pieter Huyssens in the 17th century. The Jesuit monastery was closed in 1773 and was converted into a Temple of Reason during the French Revolution - an institution intended to spread the ideas of the revolution and replace Christianity by a new belief system. The church recovered its religious function as the <strong>Saint Donatian’s Church (link to Saint Donatian’s Church)</strong> after the original on the Burg square was demolished by the French.&nbsp;</p><p>The church was officially awarded its current name in 1854. After incurring heavy damage due to a bomb explosion at the end of the <strong>First World War (link to Pro Patria Arch)</strong>, it has been a protected monument since 1939. Inside, you can admire the many Baroque architectural details and the elaborately decorated church furniture.</p>',
                'description_c' => NULL,
                'created_at' => '2021-06-08 12:32:00',
                'updated_at' => '2021-06-08 12:32:00',
                'deleted_at' => NULL,
                'url' => NULL,
            ),
            58 => 
            array (
                'id' => 59,
                'name' => 'Langerei',
                'address' => 'Langerei',
                'lat' => '51.21703524605866',
                'lng' => '3.228601770127511',
                'description_a' => '<p>Water played a pivotal role in the birth and development of Bruges. The city originated on the confluence of a number of streams that together formed the river Reie, which ran northwards through the coastal plain before eventually reaching the sea.</p>',
            'description_b' => '<p>As far back as Roman times, there was already considerable seafaring activity in this region. Sea ships could make their way into Bruges via a sea-arm called the Zwin, but due to the low water levels they could only enter during high tide. As a result of the erosion of the Zwin from the 13th century onwards, sea ships on their way to Bruges were forced to dock in outer harbours such as Sluis or Damme. There, the goods were loaded onto smaller barges and transported to Bruges via a small canal. Daily products like sardines, wine or salt, but also many fine goods and luxury products made their way to the city via this route. Over time, the silting up of the Zwin was one of the major causes of the economic decline of Bruges.&nbsp;</p><p>The Langerei largely follows the trajectory of the original river Reie through the city. The name Langerei translates into Long Canal, and it is indeed pretty long for Bruges standards. If you follow the canal until the edge of town, you will find a beautiful wooden drawbridge about halfway. From this little bridge you can see the enormous seminary, an educational institute for priests, and next to it the former hospital called <strong>Our Lady of the Pottery (link to Our Lady of the Pottery Hospital)</strong>. &nbsp;</p>',
                'description_c' => NULL,
                'created_at' => '2021-06-08 12:52:07',
                'updated_at' => '2021-06-08 12:52:07',
                'deleted_at' => NULL,
                'url' => NULL,
            ),
            59 => 
            array (
                'id' => 60,
                'name' => 'Bladelin Court',
                'address' => 'Naaldenstraat 19',
                'lat' => '51.210911785288',
                'lng' => '3.2222976399486414',
                'description_a' => '<p>Bladelin Court, a typical palazzo of the Italian Renaissance, is one of the most beautiful city palaces that remain from the Burgundian era in Bruges.</p>',
            'description_b' => '<p>The palace was built around 1440 by Pieter Bladelin, treasurer of the Order of the Golden Fleece (link to Gruuthuse) and financial administrator of Duke Philip the Good. As one of the wealthiest citizens of the Burgundian Netherlands, Pieter Bladelin built his own city, the city of Middelburg.&nbsp;</p><p>The Bladelin Court immediately transports you back to 15th-century Burgundian Bruges: an enclosed and cobbled courtyard with geometric hedges and a stately, Gothic tower - a clear testimony to the wealth of the builder. After Pieter Bladelin moved to his newly built city of Middelburg in 1451, his palace was sold to the Florentine Medici family, who installed a branch of their bank here under the direction of Tommaso Portinari. The stone medallion portraits of Lorenzo de\' Medici and his wife still adorn the elegant courtyard. In the 19th century, the building functioned as a school for lace-making.&nbsp;</p>',
                'description_c' => NULL,
                'created_at' => '2021-06-08 13:05:59',
                'updated_at' => '2021-06-08 13:05:59',
                'deleted_at' => NULL,
                'url' => NULL,
            ),
            60 => 
            array (
                'id' => 61,
                'name' => 'Prinsenhof',
                'address' => 'Ontvangersstraat 9',
                'lat' => '51.2082784992948',
                'lng' => '3.2195667734608713',
                'description_a' => '<p>The 14th century Prinsenhof or Prince’s Court was my favourite residence in Flanders and served as a political, economic and cultural centre for my Burgundian ancestors.</p>',
            'description_b' => '<p>At a time when my family ruled over a big part of Europe, including Flanders, the palace functioned as a seat of power from where we governed our vast territories. When my grandfather Philip the Good married Isabella of Portugal in 1430, the Prince’s Court was further expanded in celebration of his marriage. For the occasion, Philip also established the <strong>Order of the Golden Fleece (link to Gruuthuse Palace)</strong> here, an order of Christian knights that still exists today. Over the years, the complex was enlarged by each successive inhabitant and contained an exotic zoo, a primitive tennis court and one of the largest bathhouses in Europe. Both my grandfather and myself died here in the 15th century.</p><p>In this magnificent palace, my family was renowned for throwing the most exuberant parties, banquets and parades that anyone had ever witnessed. It was a time when Bruges thrived as a financial centre and an international metropolis attracting the rich and famous, and the Burgundian court further added to that grandeur.&nbsp;</p><p>The glory days of Bruges ended after the city had dared to challenge my husband, the Habsburg Emperor <strong>Maximilian of Austria (link to Legend of the Swans)</strong>. The city fell into decline and the illustrious monuments started to decay. The palace became obsolete and was used as a monastery for a long time until it was turned into Hotel Dukes’ Palace in 1998, only leaving a slight impression of its former splendour.</p>',
                'description_c' => NULL,
                'created_at' => '2021-06-08 13:10:50',
                'updated_at' => '2021-06-08 13:10:50',
                'deleted_at' => NULL,
                'url' => NULL,
            ),
            61 => 
            array (
                'id' => 62,
                'name' => 'Oldest City Wall',
                'address' => 'Pottenmakersstraat',
                'lat' => '51.212064937562396',
                'lng' => '3.222038875857217',
                'description_a' => '<p>The tower on the other side of the canal is part of the original defensive wall around the city, built in the twelfth century in the wake of the murder of the Flemish count in Bruges.</p>',
            'description_b' => '<p>The story of Bruges starts in the 9th century, when the land was regularly flooded by the sea and Vikings arrived from the north to trade and pillage. They docked their ships here and named this place Bryghia, meaning quay or harbour. Bryghia would later become Brugge or Bruges.</p><p>To protect the inhabitants from the Viking raids, the first margrave of Flanders, Baldwin Iron Arm, built a stone fortress on what is now the <strong>Burg square (link to Burg square)</strong>. As a protected settlement with a direct link to the North Sea, Bruges rapidly developed into a prominent international trading port, importing wool from England and exporting fine Flemish cloth to all corners of the continent. The city quickly grew rich and crowded as a result of its thriving cloth industry and favourable geographic position.</p><p>This development also defined the city’s social structure, as about half the population consisted of weavers, fullers, dyers or wool shavers. They were the backbone of the booming economy, but had to live in rather poor conditions. Most of the wealth and power was controlled by the nobility, who solidified their position by making agreements and privileges that were kept in the treasury room of our <strong>Belfry (link to Belfry and Cloth Hall)</strong>.&nbsp;</p><p>The growing influence of the newly emerging trading elite inevitably brought them into conflict with the established aristocracy and their lord, the count of Flanders. That’s what happened in 1127, when the powerful family of the Erembalds conspired against Count Charles the Good and stabbed him to death while praying inside the <strong>Saint Donatian’s Church (link to Saint Donatian’s Church)</strong>. The incident sparked a huge political crisis and forced the French King Louis VI to intervene. He had 27 conspirators responsible for the murder thrown from the highest tower of the Burg square and readily made use of the power vacuum to try to expand his influence over Flanders.&nbsp;</p><p>The people of Bruges quickly realised they needed better protection and began to build fortifications around the city, encircling it with moats, earthen walls and wooden palisades. The wooden fortification was later replaced by a stone construction and the only remnant of this first defence wall is the semi-circular guard tower visible across the canal. The moats that were dug in the weeks following the assassination still form part of the inner canals of the city today.</p><p>Bruges continued to grow to such an extent that by the end of the 13th century, new <strong>ramparts (link to City walls)</strong> were needed. These were completed around 1300 and gave the city its definitive and characteristic oval shape.</p>',
                'description_c' => NULL,
                'created_at' => '2021-06-08 13:25:20',
                'updated_at' => '2021-06-08 13:25:20',
                'deleted_at' => NULL,
                'url' => NULL,
            ),
            62 => 
            array (
                'id' => 63,
                'name' => 'Wednesday Market',
                'address' => 'Woensdagmarkt',
                'lat' => '51.2124342949693',
                'lng' => '3.226201799469397',
                'description_a' => '<p>Hallo, mein Name ist Hans Memling. Sorry about my accent, but I’m not really from here. I was born around 1433 in what is now Germany, but moved to Bruges in my thirties.</p>',
            'description_b' => '<p>Why did I do that? Because at that time, Bruges was one of the wealthiest cities in Europe and artists like myself had a very promising future here. It proved to be the right decision! When I was in my fifties, I was one of the most affluent and respected citizens in town.&nbsp;</p><p>My craft was painting, mostly religious themes for the rich patrons who ordered them. My clients were from many different nationalities, which explains why my work is found scattered around Europe today. I was also commissioned by the <strong>Saint John’s Hospital (link to Saint John’s Hospital)</strong> to paint several works, which can still be admired in the hospital’s museum. I died on the 11th of August, 1494, and my grave is located in the Saint Gillis Church, a two minute walk away from here.</p><p>If you’re wondering why my statue is here and not where I’m buried, that’s because we’re now at the former Easterling Square, which was the German quarter of the city. Like most European nations, the German population of Bruges occupied its own <strong>nation house (link to Venetian nation house)</strong>, a sort of consulate. United under the Hanseatic League, a network of Eastern European trading cities of which Bruges was an important pillar, the German population grouped together in a central meeting place that was called the Easterling House and was located just around the corner. The beautifully decorated brick tower was the tallest of all private buildings in the city and was considered one of the seven wonders of Bruges. Unfortunately, this architectural wonder was largely lost in the course of the 18th century.</p>',
                'description_c' => NULL,
                'created_at' => '2021-06-08 13:28:52',
                'updated_at' => '2021-06-08 13:28:52',
                'deleted_at' => NULL,
                'url' => NULL,
            ),
            63 => 
            array (
                'id' => 64,
                'name' => 'Guido Gezelle Square',
                'address' => 'Guido Gezelleplein',
                'lat' => '51.20529072609277',
                'lng' => '3.224028142070712',
                'description_a' => '<p>My name is Guido Gezelle, the most celebrated poet of 19th-century Flanders.&nbsp;</p>',
                'description_b' => '<p>When I was born in Bruges on May 1, 1830, it was one of the poorest cities in Belgium. The middle class spoke French and public life was conducted entirely in this language, while the illiterate lower classes only knew the local dialect. I saw it as my mission to advance the Flemish language through art and literature, so I began writing nature poems in my local dialect. In those days the literary elite rather looked down on popular poetry, so it took quite a long time before my poems were appreciated outside of my hometown of Bruges.&nbsp;</p><p>In the end, my work had a great influence on Flemish culture. Some even went as far as to call me the grandmaster of Flemish poetry, though I spent most of my time working as a priest, teacher, journalist, language scholar and translator. After my death in 1899, my birth house in Bruges was converted into a museum celebrating my life and work, which you can still visit today.</p>',
                'description_c' => NULL,
                'created_at' => '2021-06-08 13:33:24',
                'updated_at' => '2021-06-08 13:33:24',
                'deleted_at' => NULL,
                'url' => NULL,
            ),
            64 => 
            array (
                'id' => 65,
                'name' => 'English Convent',
                'address' => 'Carmersstraat 85',
                'lat' => '51.214701541347495',
                'lng' => '3.2343246552943645',
                'description_a' => '<p>The English Convent has been occupied by the Canonesses of Saint Augustine since 1629.&nbsp;</p>',
            'description_b' => '<p>The inhabitants of the convent have always devoted themselves to the education of young women. Initially a boarding school for English Catholic girls, the sisters also offered French lessons to girls from the Belgian nobility. The sisters were forced to flee to England in 1794 in the wake of the French Revolution, but returned to Bruges a few years later and haven’t left since.</p><p>For a time, the Flemish poet and priest <strong>Guido Gezelle (link to Guido Gezelle)</strong> served as rector of the English Convent and taught in the boarding school, where he died in 1899. The unique Classicist domed church and spacious 19th century landscaped garden have been well preserved.&nbsp;</p>',
                'description_c' => NULL,
                'created_at' => '2021-06-08 13:35:05',
                'updated_at' => '2021-06-08 13:35:05',
                'deleted_at' => NULL,
                'url' => NULL,
            ),
            65 => 
            array (
                'id' => 66,
                'name' => 'Our Lady of the Pottery Hospital',
