                'description_a' => '<p>The Hospital of Our Lady of the Pottery was one of the medieval care institutions in Bruges.</p>',
            'description_b' => '<p>The foundation of the hospital dates back to the 13th century and its name refers to the potters who were active along the canal. Like in the Saint John’s Hospital (link to Saint John’s Hospital), the nuns cared for pilgrims, travellers and the sick here. The veneration of a miracle statue of Our Lady gave the hospital’s church a pilgrimage status. As a result, the Baroque church interior was expanded and richly decorated.&nbsp;</p><p>Nowadays, the historic infirmary and convent are home to a museum displaying numerous works of art, religious artefacts and medical instruments from many centuries of care. The 13th-century limestone miracle statue in the church is one of the oldest preserved statues in Bruges. The miracles attributed to the statue are featured on the tapestries, in the miracle booklet with drawings and in the colorful stained glass windows.&nbsp;</p>',
